The calm waters of Prince William Sound have stymied efforts to
disperse the 11.3 million gallons of oil spilled when the tanker Exxon
Valdez hit a reef outside Valdez, the northernmost ice-free port in
the U.S.  A Coast Guard spokesman said the use of chemicals to
disperse and sink crude oil failed because the agents depend on rough
seas to break up the oil.  Officials plan to pump the remaining oil
aboard the tanker into another tanker.  Environmentalists are
concerned for two reasons: the size of the spill and the fact that it
is in such a sensitive and productive area.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d32"
