Some 10,080,000 gallons of crude oil spilled early Friday when the
tanker Exxon Valdez ran against a reef 25 miles outside Valdez,
Alaska.  One authority called it a major environmental catastrophe,
noting that the only way for the oil to escape out to sea was to
traverse the entire length of Prince William Sound thereby
contaminating the shoreline.  Other authorities criticized the slow
response to the spill and noted the danger to wildlife, especially a
key herring spawning area.  The ship struck the reef while maneuvering
to avoid icebergs.  The vessel's captain,i Joseph Hazelwood, has
worked for Exxon for 20 years.</SUM>

