The Exxon Valdez oil spill in Prince William Sound near Valdez, the
southern end of the Alaska pipeline, has been declared a disaster
area.  The toll on the waterway's abundant wildlife is mounting and
oil is spread over an area of about 100 miles.  The Exxon Co. said the
captain was not on the bridge when the accident occurred and the third
mate, who did not have a proper pilot's license, was in command.  It
is believed this action violated federal regulations.  The captain,
third mate, and a helmsman were relieved of duty and subpoenaed by the
National Transportation Safety Board.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d32"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA032789-0038"
SELECTOR="F"
SUMMARIZER="G">    

Exxon Shipping Co. said Sunday that an unqualified mate was piloting
the Exxon Valdez when it crashed, unleashing the worst oil spill in US
history, and that the tanker was involved in two separate accidents
that night in Prince William Sound.  Cleanup efforts continued slowly.
The Coast Guard served subpoenas on the captain, helmsman, and third
mate and a team from the National Transportation Safety Board arrived
Sunday to probe the cause of the accident.  Experts from wildlife and
research institutes are setting up rehabilitation centers.  The Coast
Guard maintains that Exxon itself will have to clean up the
spill.</SUM>

<SUM
