Exxon crews Tuesday finished pumping oil out of the tanker Exxon
Valdez and will attempt to move the vessel to a remote cove for
repairs.  The family of the fired Exxon Valdez captain, Joseph
Hazelwood, said that skipper wants to surrender to face criminal
charges pending advice from his lawyer.  He is accused of operating
the ship while under the influence of alcohol, reckless endangerment,
and negligent discharge of oil.  A multi-million dollar class-action
lawsuit was filed in federal court in California against Exxon Corp.,
charging that the spill has led to gas prices of 10 to 15 cents more a
gallon.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d32"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA043089-0197"
SELECTOR="F"
SUMMARIZER="G">    

The Coast Guard confirmed Saturday that a fresh oil sheen has seeped
from the ruptured Exxon Valdez and a complete cleanup of the tanker is
impossible.  Oil clinging to the tanks inside mixes with water and
causes sheen that is impossible to remove unless the tanker is
steam-cleaned, and nobody intends to do that.  Also, nobody in the
other states wants it, and it may go to a foreign port.  The Alaska
State Senate passed several bills aimed at protection from another
devastating spill.  Exxon has paid out $500,000 to fishermen on claims
of lost work and is processing 300 more.</SUM>

<SUM
