TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP890501-0176"
SELECTOR="F"
SUMMARIZER="G">    

Exxon officials Monday released a revised plan for cleansing 364 miles
of Alaskan coastline fouled by the nation's largest oil spill.  Since
March 24, when an Exxon tanker struck a reef outside Valdez and poured
more than 10 million gallons of crude into Prince William Sound, Exxon
has financed cleanup crews.  The company's strategy divides Alaska's
oil-tainted shores into four categories from the most heavily polluted
to the "only lightly oiled."  The worst areas would be targeted
immediately.  The gunk or sludge that resists treatment will be burned
or buried.  Both methods likely will require exemptions from local
environmental laws.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d32"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP890502-0205"
SELECTOR="F"
SUMMARIZER="G">    

The Coast Guard Commandant Paul Yost, the top federal official
tracking the Exxon plan to clean up the Alaskan oil spill, said the
plan was poorly drafted and lacking in specifics.  He did not reject
it, saying he wanted to meet with Exxon and state officials.  Consumer
activist Ralph Nader and others blasted Exxon for failing to be
prepared for the spill and not rapidly responding to the accident.
They also questioned increases in gas prices and called for a boycott
of Exxon.  Yost said he would make a decision on the plan within the
week.  Exxon called the boycott unjust.</SUM>

<SUM
