SUMMARIZER="G">    

Exxon salvage crews successfully refloated the stricken tanker Exxon
Valdez on Wednesday as its former captain surrendered to authorities
in New York to face criminal charges in the oil spill.  The tanker
refloat went well and it was taken to a cove on uninhabited Naked
Island 25 miles to the southwest.  Exxon officials were reluctant to
discuss where the tanker would be taken for permanent repairs.  No
people have been killed or seriously injured but oil has seriously
disrupted the rich Prince William Sound fishing industry.  Animal
rescue teams estimate the spill has killed several thousand birds and
hundreds of sea otters.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d32"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA040789-0051"
SELECTOR="F"
SUMMARIZER="G">    

Because of the Exxon Valdez oil spill, Alaska's governor threatened to
close down the trans- Alaska oil pipeline unless its owners meet his
state-ordered terms for improved safety and cleanup measures.  Even if
overturned, the closedown would last long enough to drive home a point
about cleanup response.  The oil pipeline owners have offered a list
of ideas.  Federal officials are probing the possibility that the
Exxon Valdez was on autopilot shortly before it ran aground and that
the electronic navigation aid confused the third mate, who complained
that he was unable to get the vessel to respond to the helm.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d32"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA012590-0174"
SELECTOR="F"
SUMMARIZER="G">    

Exxon Corp. increased its estimate of the total 1989 costs of cleaning
up the massive Alaskan oil spill to $2 billion dollars and another
$500 million will be taken in the fourth quarter for cleanup costs.
The figure does not include liability from more than 150 lawsuits that
Exxon faces from the spill.  The fourth quarter charge is in addition
to $880 million set aside in the first and second quarters, bring
Exxon's total cleanup costs for the year to $1.38 billion.  Exxon's
size is said to insulate it from serious long-term financial damage.
Exxon's stock could suffer from continuing negative publicity.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d32"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP900313-0191"
SELECTOR="F"
SUMMARIZER="G">    

A year after the wreck of the Exxon Valdez, the Alaskan environmental
authorities report that hundreds of gallons of oil are locked up under
hundreds of beaches all over Prince William Sound.  The worst is over
but assessing the continuing damage has just begun.  When Exxon's $2
billion dollar cleanup ended in mid-September, it had recovered only 5
to 9 percent of the oil spilled.  Thousands of animals and birds have
died.  The skipper of the Exxon Valdez is scheduled for trial and a
federal grand jury issue criminal indictments against Exxon, which
already faces more than 150 civil lawsuits.</SUM>

